05155nam a22007575i 9780824853716DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248537167 a10.1515/97808248537162doi  a(DE-B1597)483981  a(OCoLC)947838103  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aARC0160002bisacsh0481pa720qDE-1011 aFlath, James A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTraces of the Sage :bMonument, Materiality, and the First Temple of Confucius /cJames A. Flath; ed. by Xing Ruan, Ronald G. Knapp. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b10 color, 37 b&w illustrations, 12 charts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSpatial Habitus: Making and Meaning in Asia's Architecture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tNote on Terms and Dates -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Kong Temple as Structure -- t3. Ritual as Material Culture -- t4. Kong Temple as Space -- t5. Kong Temple and the Modern Politics of Culture -- t6. Kong Temple Inc -- t7. Epilogue -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Temple of Confucius (Kong Temple) in Qufu is the definitive monument to the world's greatest sage. From its humble origins deep in China's past, the home of Confucius grew in size and stature under the auspices of almost every major dynasty until it was the largest and most richly endowed temple in the Ming and Qing empires. The decline of state-sponsored ritualism in the twentieth century triggered a profound identity crisis for the temple and its worshipers, yet the fragile relic survived decades of neglect, war, and revolution and is now recognized as a national treasure and a World Heritage Site. Traces of the Sage is the first comprehensive account of the history and material culture of Kong Temple. Following the temple's development through time and across space, it relates architecture to the practice of Confucianism, explains the temple's phenomenal perseverance, and explores the culture of building in China. Other chapters consider the problem of Confucian heritage conservation and development over the last hundred years—a period when the validity of Confucianism has been called into question—and the challenge of remaking Confucian heritage as a commercial enterprise. By reconstructing its "social life," the study interprets Kong Temple as an active site of transaction and negotiation and argues that meaning does not hide behind architecture but emerges from the circulation and regeneration of its spaces and materials.The most complete work on a seminal monument in Chinese history through millennia, Traces of the Sage will find a ready audience among cultural and political historians of imperial and modern China as well as students and scholars of architectural history and theory and Chinese ritual.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aARCHITECTURE / Buildings / Religious.2bisacsh1 aKnapp, Ronald G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRuan, Xing, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311056413608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066323540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082485371640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824853716423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824853716.jpg  a978-3-11-056413-6  UHP eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a9